{
  "slug": "dune-2-pushed-back-barbenheimers-2-billion-and-everything-we",
  "title": "‘Dune 2’ Pushed Back, Barbenheimer’s $2 Billion, and Everything We Missed While We Were Out",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2023-08-28",
  "runtimeMin": 123,
  "format": "Back from a month off, Sean and Amanda catch up on the summer they skipped: Barbenheimer clearing $2 billion, the strike-driven ‘Dune: Part Two’ delay, and a dozen August releases from ‘Bottoms’ to ‘Heart of Stone.’ Then Sean talks to Emma Seligman about ‘Bottoms.’ Bobby Wagner produces.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The news we missed",
      "note": "Barbenheimer's $2 billion and the 'Dune 2' delay",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Barbie",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Past $1 billion and, in Amanda's read, the rare billion-dollar movie that's actually good; the pair debate whether Hollywood learns 'trust auteurs' or just 'make more toy movies.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Oppenheimer",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Headed toward $800–900M, the other half of a ~$2B Barbenheimer that Sean says put him nearer the center of the culture than he'd felt in a decade."
        },
        {
          "title": "Avatar: The Way of Water",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Sean's reminder that it has outgrossed both films combined: a phenomenon with, as they joke, a footprint of having no footprint."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Pushed by the strikes to March 15, 2024 in a mid-recording pickup: the delay guts November and reopens Best Director and Best Picture slots."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Villeneuve's first, a 2021 Best Picture nominee; the sequel was expected to be a Return of the King-style awards centerpiece."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Three we lost",
      "note": "Friedkin, Reubens, Robertson",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The French Connection",
          "year": 1971,
          "note": "William Friedkin, a past guest and, per Sean, 'such a fucking asshole from Chicago' in the most loving way, and an essential filmmaker."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Exorcist",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The line-around-the-block hit that let Friedkin overwhelm the culture."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sorcerer",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Among the great undiscovered Friedkins Sean urges people to seek out."
        },
        {
          "title": "To Live and Die in L.A.",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Sean's pick of the later Friedkin films everyone should watch."
        },
        {
          "title": "Pee-wee's Big Adventure",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Tim Burton's first feature and the gateway to Paul Reubens, 'a true one of one' comic mind for an 80s baby."
        },
        {
          "title": "Buffy the Vampire Slayer",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "One of the many other things Reubens was wonderful in."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blow",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Another Reubens turn Sean singles out."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Waltz",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "Robbie Robertson, Scorsese's consigliere; wouldn't exist without him. He scored the coming 'Killers of the Flower Moon.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Everything we missed: the movies",
      "note": "the August rundown",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Bottoms",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Emma Seligman's high-school fight-club comedy with Rachel Sennott and Ayo Adebiri. Sean laughed harder than at almost anything this year; both grant the plot bends to serve its set pieces. Nicholas Galitzine plays the dim quarterback, with Marshawn Lynch and Kaia Gerber."
        },
        {
          "title": "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: Mutant Mayhem",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The seventh Turtles film, animated, shepherded by Seth Rogen and Point Grey. Both found it charming and a little sad (childhood regurgitated at 40) before the obligatory oversized final fight. Voice cast of actual teenagers plus Rogen, Maya Rudolph, Paul Rudd, Ice Cube, Giancarlo Esposito."
        },
        {
          "title": "Strays",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Josh Greenbaum's talking-dog comedy (Will Ferrell, Jamie Foxx, Isla Fisher, Randall Park). Neither laughed; Amanda found it mean to dogs. The narrating-bulldog bit (maybe Josh Gad) drew the lone real laugh."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blue Beetle",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Ángel Manuel Soto's film with Xolo Maridueña, the first forward-facing Latino superhero movie, all but abandoned in the DCEU-to-Gunn handoff. Strong first 45 minutes (family, George Lopez, Susan Sarandon camping) before the standard noisy CG last hour."
        },
        {
          "title": "Passages",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Ira Sachs' film with Franz Rogowski, Ben Whishaw, and Adèle Exarchopoulos; a gay couple's marriage detonates over an affair. Released unrated after refusing an NC-17. One of Sean's favorites of the year, Rogowski a chaotic marvel."
        },
        {
          "title": "Red, White & Royal Blue",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Amazon's adaptation of Casey McQuiston's 2019 novel; the first son and a British prince fall in love. Both bored by its inert romance-novel stakes and Uma Thurman's badly off Texas-accented president. A streaming hit on the book's fanbase and Nicholas Galitzine anyway."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Voyage of the Demeter",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "André Øvredal's period horror from the ship's-log chapter of 'Dracula.' Well staged, thinly written; Sean wishes they'd hidden the Dracula reveal rather than leading with it. Corey Hawkins, Liam Cunningham, David Dastmalchian."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sound of Freedom",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Angel Studios' child-trafficking thriller with Jim Caviezel, a ~$180M hit on its pay-it-forward ticket scheme. Sean calls the film middling but singles out ten-plus minutes of Bill Camp."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heart of Stone",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Tom Harper's Netflix spy movie with Gal Gadot as a hidden super-agent serving a benevolent AI called 'the Heart.' Both found it astonishingly bad: a twist no one buys and a pro-AI message that lands badly at this moment."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dreamin' Wild",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Bill Pohlad's follow-up to 'Love & Mercy,' the story of the Emerson brothers' rediscovered 1970s record. Casey Affleck, Walton Goggins, Zooey Deschanel, Beau Bridges. Sean liked its portrait of a stuck, un-heroic artist whose music is still great."
        },
        {
          "title": "They Cloned Tyrone",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Juel Taylor's directorial debut (John Boyega, Teyonah Parris, Jamie Foxx), a blaxploitation-tinged sci-fi cloning conspiracy. Sean's favorite of the Netflix batch; a real filmmaker's movie that sags in the third act."
        },
        {
          "title": "River Wild",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Netflix's side-sequel to the 1994 whitewater thriller (Adam Brody, Leighton Meester, Taran Killam). A gnarly, well-made 'nobody makes these anymore' Sean-and-Amanda watch."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Emma Seligman on ‘Bottoms’",
      "guest": "Emma Seligman on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Bottoms",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Written with Rachel Sennott and kept deliberately absurd and bloody: Heathers and Jawbreaker by way of Kick-Ass. Cast to play it straight; Marshawn Lynch improvised his way in without knowing why she wanted him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Shiva Baby",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Her personal, one-location debut with Sennott: the grounded, 'traumatic' opposite of the freeing 'Bottoms.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Smoking Tigers",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The coming-of-age debut she caught on a Tribeca jury; her pick for the last great thing she's seen."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
